h|13.70}}13.70%\n|{{sortname|Anthony|Davis}}\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|[[2013 NBA draft|2013]]\n|align=\"left\"|[[Cleveland Cavaliers]]\n|24\u201358 (3rd-worst)\n|156 (out of 1000)\n|{{Ntsh|15.60}}15.60%\n|{{sortname|Anthony|Bennett|dab=basketball}}\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|[[2014 NBA draft|2014]]\n|align=\"left\"|[[Cleveland Cavaliers]]<br><small>(later traded to [[Minnesota Timberwolves|Minnesota]] before playing)</small>\n|33\u201349 (9th-worst)\n|17 (out of 1000)\n|{{Ntsh|1.70}}1.70%\n|{{sortname|Andrew|Wiggins}}\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|[[2015 NBA draft|2015]]\n|align=\"left\"|[[Minnesota Timberwolves]]\n|16\u201366 (Worst)\n|250 (out of 1000)\n|{{Ntsh|25.00}}25.00%\n|{{sortname|Karl-Anthony|Towns}}\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|[[2016 NBA draft|2016]]\n|align=\"left\"|[[Philadelphia 76ers]]\n|10\u201372 (Worst)\n|250 (out of 1000)\n|{{Ntsh|25.00}}25.00%\n|{{sortname|Ben|Simmons}}\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|[[2017 NBA draft|2017]]\n|align=\"left\"|[[Brooklyn Nets]]<br><small>(conveyed to the [[Philadelphia 76ers]] via the [[Boston Celtics]])</small>\n|20\u201362 (Worst)\n|250 (out of 1000)\n|{{Ntsh|25.00}}25.00%\n|{{sortname|Markelle|Fultz}}\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|[[2018 NBA draft|2018]]\n|align=\"left\"|[[Phoenix Suns]] \n|21-61 (Worst)\n|250 (out of 1000)\n|{{Ntsh|25.00}}25.00%\n|{{sortname|Deandre|Ayton}}\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|[[2019 NBA draft|2019]]\n|align=\"left\"|[[New Orleans Pelicans]]\n|33-49 (T-7th-worst)\n|60 (out of 1000)\n|{{Ntsh|6.00}}6.00%\n|{{sortname|Zion|Williamson}}\n|-\n|align=center|[[2020 NBA draft|2020]]\n|colspan=5|TBA\n|}\n;Notes\n{{reflist|group=lower-alpha}}\n\n==See also==\n*{{Portal-inline|Sports}}\n\n==References==\n;General\n{{Refbegin}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/history/draft_evolution.html|title=Evolution of the Draft and Lottery|accessdate=August 22, 2009|work=NBA.com|publisher=Turner Sports Interactive, Inc|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101203184544/http://www.nba.com/history/draft_evolution.html|archive-date=December 3, 2010|url-status=dead}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/history/lottery_probabilities.html|title=Year-by-Year Lottery Probabilities|accessdate=August 22, 2009|work=NBA.com|publisher=Turner Sports Interactive, Inc|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6BDcBKWed?url=http://www.nba.com/history/lottery_probabilities.html|archive-date=October 6, 2012|url-status=dead}}\n{{Refend}}\n;Specific\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.nba.com/ NBA.com]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20090315112610/http://www.nba.com/history/draft_index.html NBA.com: NBA Draft History]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20100523120216/http://www.thehoopsreport.com/article.aspx?id=499 The Hoops Report: NBA Draft Lottery]\n\n{{NBA Drafts}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Nba Draft Lottery}}\n[[Category:National Basketball Association draft|Draft Lottery]]\n[[Category:Recurring events established in 1985]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Lottery process to determine the order of the NBA draft}}\nThe '''NBA draft lottery''' is an annual event held by the [[National Basketball Association]] (NBA), in which the teams who had missed the [[NBA Playoffs|playoffs]] the previous year participate in a [[lottery]] process to determine the [[Draft (sports)|draft]] order in the [[NBA draft]]. The NBA Draft lottery started in 1985. In the NBA draft, the teams obtain the rights to amateur U.S. [[college basketball]] players and other [[Eligibility for the NBA draft|eligible players]], including international players. The lottery winner would get the [[List of first overall NBA draft picks|first selection]] in the draft. The term \"lottery pick\" denotes a draft pick whose position is determined through the lottery, while the non-playoff teams involved in the process are often called \"lottery teams.\"\n\nUnder the current rules, only the top four picks are decided by the lottery, and are chosen from the 14 teams that do not make the playoffs. The team with the worst record, or the team that holds the draft rights of the team with the worst record, has the best chance to obtain a higher draft pick. After the top four positions are selected (from the lottery slotting system), the remainder of the first-round draft order is in inverse order of the win-loss record for the remaining teams, or the teams who originally held the lottery rights if they were traded. The lottery does not determine the draft order in the subsequent rounds of the draft.\n\nBeginning with the 2019 draft, the NBA changed the lottery odds (the bottom three teams will all have an equal 14% chance of winning the top pick) and increased the number of teams selected in the lottery from three to four.\n\n==History==\n\n===1947\u20131965: Territorial picks===\n{{further|NBA territorial pick}}\nIn the earlier drafts, the teams would draft in reverse order of their win-loss record. However, a special [[NBA territorial pick|territorial-pick]] rule allowed a team to draft a player from its local area. If a team decided to use its territorial pick, it forfeited its first-round pick in the draft.<ref name=\"Inside\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/features/inside_lottery_050524.html|title=Let the Ping-Pong Balls Fall|last=Dengate|first=Jeff|date=May 16, 2007|accessdate=August 22, 2009|work=NBA.com|publisher=Turner Sports Interactive, Inc|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/68Oj2mcnc?url=http://www.nba.com/features/inside_lottery_050524.html|archive-date=June 13, 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n===1966\u20131984: Coin flip===\nIn 1966, the NBA revamped its draft system, and introduced a coin flip between the worst teams in each conference to determine who would obtain the first overall draft pick. The team who lost the coin flip would get the second pick, and the rest of the first-round picks were determined in reverse order of the win-loss record.\n\nThe coin-flip system gave the worst teams in each conference an equal chance to have the first draft pick, but had a disadvantage  in that the two worst teams overall could be in the same conference; in this situation, the second-worst team overall would have no chance of obtaining the first draft pick.<ref name=\"Inside\"/>\n\n===1985\u20131989: Early lottery system===\nAfter the [[1984 NBA draft|1984]] coin flip, which was won by the [[Houston Rockets]], the NBA introduced the lottery system to counter the accusations that the Rockets and several other teams were deliberately losing their regular season games in order to secure the worst record and consequently the chance to obtain the first pick.<ref name=\"NYDailyNews\">{{cite news|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/archives/sports/2005/05/22/2005-05-22_the_draft_that_changed_it_al.html |title=The Draft That Changed It All. Tanks to '84, the lottery was born |last=Bondy |first=Filip |date=May 22, 2005 |accessdate=August 22, 2009 |work=NYDailyNews.com |publisher=Daily News, L.P |location=New York |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/600WDBDwj?url=http://articles.nydailynews.com/2005-05-22/sports/18292722_1_lottery-flips-draft-ladder |archivedate=July 7, 2011 }}</ref><ref name=\"USAToday\">{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/sports/basketball/nba/2007-06-24-draft-lookback_N.htm|title=25 drafts, dozens of stars, one Michael|last=DuPree|first=David|date=June 25, 2007|accessdate=August 22, 2009|work=USA Today}}</ref> The lottery system involved a random drawing of an envelope from a hopper. Inside each of the envelopes was the name of a non-playoff team. The team whose envelope was drawn first would get the first pick. The process was then repeated until the rest of the lottery picks were determined. In this system, each non-playoff team had an equal chance to obtain the first pick. The rest of the first-round picks were determined in reverse order of the win-loss record.<ref name=\"SportingNews\">{{cite web|url=http://www.sportingnews.com/nba/articles/20070328/849887-p.html|title=Tanking games? If only NBA's bad teams were that good|last=Litke|first=Jim|date=March 28, 2007|accessdate=August 22, 2009|work=SportingNews.com|publisher=Sporting News}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref>\n\nStarting from 1987, the NBA modified the lottery system so that only the first three picks were determined by the lottery. After the three envelopes were drawn, the remaining non-playoff teams would select in reverse order of their win-loss record. This meant that the team with the worst record could receive no worse than the fourth selection, and the second-worst team could pick no lower than fifth, and so on.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_qn4188/is_20070522/ai_n19166711/|title=League has used variety of methods to determine No. 1 pick|date=May 22, 2007|work=The Indianapolis Star|accessdate=October 4, 2009}}</ref>\n\nThe [[New York Knicks]] were the first winner of the lottery in 1985. They selected [[Georgetown Hoyas men's basketball|Georgetown University]] standout [[Patrick Ewing]] with their first overall pick. However, speculation arose that the NBA had rigged the lottery so that the Knicks would be assured to get the first pick.<ref name=\"NYDailyNews\"/><ref name=\"USAToday\"/><ref name=\"SportingNews\"/> Even though the envelope system was highly criticized, it was used until [[1989 NBA draft|1989]] before being replaced by the weighted lottery system in [[1990 NBA draft|1990]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/2009/news/features/fran_blinebury/05/19/lottery/|title=Winning the Lottery is easy; picking the right player is not|last=Blinebury|first=Fran|date=May 19, 2009|accessdate=August 22, 2009|work=NBA.com|publisher=Turner Sports Interactive, Inc|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090523201822/http://www.nba.com/2009/news/features/fran_blinebury/05/19/lottery/|archivedate=May 23, 2009}}</ref>\n\n===Since 1990: Weighted lottery system===\nIn 1990, the NBA changed the format of the lottery to give the team with the worst record the best chance of landing the first pick. The worst non-playoff team that season would have 11 chances, out of 66, to obtain the first pick. The second worst would have 10 chances, and so on. Similarly to the previous system, the weighted lottery system was also used only to determine the first three picks, while the rest of the teams selected in reverse order of their win-loss records.\n\nDespite the weighted odds, the [[Orlando Magic]] managed to win the lottery in [[1993 NBA draft|1993]] with only one chance to obtain the first pick as it was the best non-playoff team in the [[1992\u201393 NBA season|previous season]]. In October 1993, the NBA modified the lottery system to give the team with the worst record a higher chance to win the draft lottery and to decrease the better teams' chances to win. The new system increased the chances of the worst team obtaining the first pick in the draft from 16.7 percent to 25 percent, while decreasing the chances of the best non-playoff team from 1.5 percent to 0.5 percent.\n\nIn the new system, 14 numbered [[table tennis]] balls were used. Then, a four-number combination from the 14 balls were drawn to determine the lottery winner. Prior to the draft, the NBA assigns 1,000 possible combinations to the non-playoff teams (the 11\u201312\u201313\u201314 combination is ignored and redrawn). The process was then repeated to determine the second and third pick.<ref name=\"Inside\"/> The table below shows the lottery chances and the probabilities for each team to win the first pick in the weighted lottery system in 1993 and 1994 draft.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ajur.uni.edu/v2n3/Florke%20&%20Ecker.pdf|title=NBA Draft Lottery Probabilities|last=Florke|first=Chad R.|author2=Ecker, Mark D.|date=December 1, 2003|accessdate=August 22, 2009|format=PDF|work=|publisher=University of Northern Iowa}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, the NBA Board of Governors voted on a proposed reform to the lottery.<ref>{{cite web|title=Lottery Reform Vote Set to Pass?|url=http://www.basketballinsiders.com/lottery-reform-vote-set-to-pass/|website=basketballinsiders.com}}</ref> If the proposed changes passed, the four worst teams in the league would have been given identical odds (around 11 percent) at winning the top pick. The fifth team would have a 10 percent chance and the odds would decrease for each team picking after.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Higin|first1=Sean|title=Report: Board of Governors expected to pass draft lottery reform, Sixers and Thunder opposed|url=http://probasketballtalk.nbcsports.com/2014/10/20/report-board-of-governors-expected-to-pass-draft-lottery-reform-sixers-and-thunder-opposed/|website=probasketballtalk.com|accessdate=October 21, 2014}}</ref> The proposed changes were designed to disincentivize having the worst record in the league (at the time, the worst team was given a 25% chance at the top pick) and keep teams competitive throughout the entire season.\nThe final vote was 17-13 in favor of the reform, short of the 23 votes in favor required to push the change through.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/nba/story/_/id/11744283/nba-owners-fail-pass-draft-lottery-reform|title=Lottery reform falls short of passing|publisher=ESPN|date=October 22, 2014|accessdate=April 20, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, [[Dikembe Mutombo]] made people question the draft's legitimacy when he prematurely tweeted a congratulatory message to the [[Philadelphia 76ers]] for receiving the first pick hours before the lottery was conducted. Philadelphia did indeed win the first overall pick.<ref>http://www.foxsports.com/nba/story/dikembe-mutombo-tweet-nba-draft-lottery-rigged-76ers-sixers-philadelphia-051716</ref> Further questions were raised a bit when the NBA Draft revealed that every spot remained exactly the same as it was before the event took place, which was the first occurrence in draft lottery history. A year later, Lakers executive [[Magic Johnson]] raised even further questions about the draft process with him assuring head coach [[Luke Walton]] that the Lakers would acquire a top 3 pick for the [[2017 NBA draft]] after an interview Walton had on May 4, 2017, twelve days before the draft lottery commenced and moved up to the second pick.<ref>https://www.sbnation.com/2017/5/4/15543124/luke-walton-magic-johnson-draft-pick-lakers</ref>\n\nIn response to teams like the [[Philadelphia 76ers]] deliberately seeking high-loss season records in order to improve their draft odds, beginning with the [[2019 NBA draft]] the NBA implemented a new lottery system giving the worst three teams equal odds at the first overall pick and expanding the lottery to the top four picks (up from the top three picks). As with the changes proposed in 2014, these changes were intended to disincentivize high-loss seasons by flattening the odds of getting the top pick and increasing the likelihood of the worst teams having to pick later in the draft.\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:right\"\n!rowspan=\"2\"|\n! colspan=\"4\" |1993 draft lottery\n!rowspan=\"13\"|\n! colspan=\"4\" |1994 draft lottery\n|-\n!Team!![[1992\u201393 NBA season|1992\u20131993<br>record]]!!Chances<br>(out of 66)!!Probability\n!Team!![[1993\u201394 NBA season|1993\u20131994<br>record]]!!Chances<br>(out of 1000)!!Probability\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|1\n|align=\"left\"|[[Dallas Mavericks|Dallas]]\n|11\u201371||11||16.67%\n|align=\"left\"|Dallas\n|13\u201369||250||25.00%\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|2\n|align=\"left\"|[[Minnesota Timberwolves|Minnesota]]\n|19\u201363||10||15.15%\n|align=\"left\"|[[Detroit Pistons|Detroit]]\n|20\u201362||164||16.40%\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|3\n|align=\"left\"|[[Washington Wizards|Washington]]\n|22\u201360||9||13.64%\n|align=\"left\"|Minnesota\n|20\u201362||164||16.40%\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|4\n|align=\"left\"|[[Sacramento Kings|Sacramento]]\n|25\u201357||8||12.12%\n|align=\"left\"|[[Milwaukee Bucks|Milwaukee]]\n|20\u201362||163||16.30%\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|5\n|align=\"left\"|[[Philadelphia 76ers|Philadelphia]]\n|26\u201356||7||10.61%\n|align=\"left\"|Washington\n|24\u201358||94||9.40%\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|6\n|align=\"left\"|Milwaukee\n|28\u201354||6||9.09%\n|align=\"left\"|Philadelphia\n|25\u201357||66||6.60%\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|7\n|align=\"left\"|[[Golden State Warriors|Golden State]]\n|34\u201348||5||7.58%\n|align=\"left\"|[[Los Angeles Clippers|L.A. Clippers]]\n|27\u201355||44||4.40%\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|8\n|align=\"left\"|[[Denver Nuggets|Denver]]\n|36\u201346||4||6.06%\n|align=\"left\"|Sacramento\n|28\u201354||27||2.70%\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|9\n|align=\"left\"|[[Miami Heat|Miami]]\n|36\u201346||3||4.55%\n|align=\"left\"|[[Boston Celtics|Boston]]\n|32\u201350||15||1.50%\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|10\n|align=\"left\"|Detroit\n|40\u201342||2||3.03%\n|align=\"left\"|[[Los Angeles Lakers|L.A. Lakers]]\n|33\u201349||8||0.80%\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|11\n|align=\"left\"|[[Orlando Magic|Orlando]]\n|41\u201341||1||1.52%\n|align=\"left\"|[[Charlotte Hornets|Charlotte]]\n|41\u201341||5||0.50%\n|}\n\nIn 1995, the NBA had an agreement with the two expansion franchises, the [[Toronto Raptors]] and the [[Memphis Grizzlies|Vancouver Grizzlies]] that neither team would be eligible to obtain the first overall pick in the [[1996 NBA draft|1996]], [[1997 NBA draft|1997]] and [[1998 NBA draft|1998 draft]]s. The Raptors won the 1996 lottery but were forced to settle for the second pick. Another combination was drawn and resulted in the [[Philadelphia 76ers]] getting the first pick.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/archives/sports/2003/01/12/2003-01-12__new__charlotte_gets_fast_br.html |title='New' Charlotte Gets Fast Break |last=Lawrence |first=Mitch |date=January 12, 2003 |accessdate=August 22, 2009 |work=NYDailyNews.com |publisher=Daily News, L.P |location=New York |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/61Gyf8WsP?url=http://articles.nydailynews.com/2003-01-12/sports/18223903_1_raptors-salary-cap-griz |archivedate=August 28, 2011 }}</ref> Two years later, the Grizzlies won the lottery and likewise had to pick second in the draft, while the [[Los Angeles Clippers|L.A. Clippers]] obtained the first pick.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/1998/05/17/archive/main9629.shtml|title=Clippers Get Pick Of The Litter|date=May 17, 1998|accessdate=August 22, 2009|work=CBS News|publisher=CBS Interactive Inc}}</ref> The Raptors did not pick first until [[2006 NBA draft|2006]], when they won the lottery as the fifth-worst non-playoff team. The Grizzlies have yet to hold the first selection.\n\n==Process==\nThe lottery is normally held during either the third or fourth week of May.\n\nTo determine the winner, fourteen ping pong balls numbered 1\u201314 are placed in a standard lottery machine and four balls are randomly selected from the lot. Just as in most traditional lotteries, the order in which the numbers are drawn is not important. That is, 1\u20132\u20133\u20134 is considered to be the same as 4\u20133\u20132\u20131. There are a total of 1,001 [[combination]]s (or (14x13x12x11) / (4x3x2x1)). Of these combinations, one outcome is disregarded and the remaining outcomes are distributed among the 14 non-playoff NBA teams.  The combination 11\u201312\u201313\u201314 (in any order that those numbers are drawn) is not assigned and is ignored if drawn; this has never occurred in practice.\n\nIn the event a lottery pick is traded to another team, the record of the original team (whose pick it was before the trade) still determines eligibility for the lottery, and assignment of chances.\n\n=== 2005 ===\nSince 2005, with 30 NBA teams, 16 qualify for the playoffs and the remaining 14 teams enter in the draft lottery. These 14 teams were ranked in reverse order of their regular season record and assigned the following number of chances, up to 2018:\n\n# 250 combinations, 25.0% chance of receiving the No. 1 pick\n# 199 combinations, 19.9% chance\n# 156 combinations, 15.6% chance\n# 119 combinations, 11.9% chance\n# 88 combinations, 8.8% chance\n# 63 combinations, 6.3% chance\n# 43 combinations, 4.3% chance\n# 28 combinations, 2.8% chance\n# 17 combinations, 1.7% chance\n# 11 combinations, 1.1% chance\n# 8 combinations, 0.8% chance\n# 7 combinations, 0.7% chance\n# 6 combinations, 0.6% chance\n# 5 combinations, 0.5% chance\n\nThe following table listed the odds for each seed to get specific picks if there were no ties (rounded to 9 decimal places).\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Seed  \n! Chances\n! 1st\n! 2nd\n! 3rd\n! 4th\n! 5th\n! 6th\n! 7th\n! 8th\n! 9th\n! 10th\n! 11th\n! 12th\n! 13th\n! 14th\n|-\n| align=\"left\" | 1\n| 250 || .250 || .215101163 || .177734929|| .357163908 || \u2013 || \u2013 || \u2013 || \u2013 || \u2013 || \u2013 || \u2013 || \u2013 || \u2013 || \u2013\n|-\n| align=\"left\" | 2\n| 199 || .199 || .188114409 || .171234801 ||.318576518\t||.123074273|| \u2013 || \u2013 || \u2013 || \u2013 || \u2013 || \u2013 || \u2013 || \u2013 || \u2013\n|-\n| align=\"left\" | 3\n| 156 || .156 || .157389003 || .155857379 ||.225714514\t||.264773169\t||.040265935||\t- ||\t- ||\t- ||\t- ||\t- ||\t- ||\t- ||\t-\n|-\n| align=\"left\" | 4\n| 119 || .119 || .125981041 || .132996432 ||.09854506\t||.35066839\t||.160343509\t||.012465569||\t- ||\t- ||\t- ||\t- ||\t- ||\t- ||\t-\n|-\n| align=\"left\" | 5\n| 88 || .088 || .096557715 || .106805367 ||-||.261484169\t||.359914729\t||.083574781\t||.00366324||\t- ||\t- ||\t- ||\t- ||\t- ||\t-\n|-\n| align=\"left\" | 6\n| 63 || .063 || .070969634 || .081162814 || \u2013 || \u2013 ||.439475827\t||.304681369\t||.039678831\t||.001031526\t||- ||\t- ||\t- ||\t- ||\t-\n|-\n| align=\"left\" | 7\n| 43 || .043 || .049398654 || .057875089 || \u2013 || \u2013 || \u2013 ||.599278281\t||.232216227\t||.017945796\t||.000285953\t||- ||\t- ||\t- ||\t-\n|-\n| align=\"left\" | 8\n| 28 || .028 || .032618079 || .03886176 || \u2013 || \u2013 || \u2013 || \u2013 ||.724441702\t||.167947535\t||.008050813\t||.000080110\t||- ||\t- ||\t-\n|-\n| align=\"left\" | 9\n| 17 || .017 || .019999548 || .024106498 || \u