| .134173189\t|| .127486524\t|| .119720474\t|| .478619813\t ||  -\t ||  -\t ||  -\t ||  -\t ||  -\t ||  -\t ||  -\t ||  -\t ||  -\n|-\n| align=\"left\" | 2\n| 140 || .14\t|| .134173189\t|| .127486524\t|| .119720474\t|| .278393796\t|| .200226017\t ||  -\t ||  -\t ||  -\t ||  -\t ||  -\t ||  -\t ||  -\t ||  -\n|-\n| align=\"left\" | 3\n| 140 || .140 || .134173189\t|| .127486524\t|| .119720474\t|| .148385792\t|| .260016008 ||  .070218013\t ||  -\t ||  -\t ||  -\t ||  -\t ||  -\t ||  -\t ||  -\n|-\n| align=\"left\" | 4\n| 125 || .125 || .122289184\t|| .118908682\t|| .114620847\t|| .072434116\t|| .257408144\t|| .167431573\t|| .021907454\t ||  -\t ||  -\t ||  -\t ||  -\t ||  -\t ||  -\n|-\n| align=\"left\" | 5\n| 105 || .105 || .105404479\t|| .105554544\t|| .105280805\t|| .022166482\t|| .196105398\t|| .267446506\t|| .086844691\t|| .006197095\t ||  -\t ||  -\t ||  -\t ||  -\t ||  - \n|-\n| align=\"left\" | 6\n| 90 || .090 || .092004257\t|| .094086561\t|| .096180446\t ||  -\t|| .086244433\t|| .297661037\t|| .205496061\t|| .036835452\t|| .001491753\t ||  -\t ||  -\t ||  -\t ||  -\n|-\n| align=\"left\" | 7\n| 75 || .075 || .078006715\t|| .081378484\t|| .085165485\t ||  -\t ||  -\t|| .197242872\t|| .341095198\t|| .128807111\t|| .013008381\t|| .000295753\t ||  -\t ||  -\t ||  -\n|-\n| align=\"left\" | 8\n| 60 || .060 || .06344045\t|| .067445898\t|| .072168277\t ||  -\t ||  -\t ||  -\t|| .344656595\t|| .320976116\t|| .067470015\t|| .003796226\t|| .0000464223\t ||  -\t ||  -\n|-\n| align=\"left\" | 9\n| 45 || .045\t|| .048332259\t|| .052311782\t|| .057152759\t ||  -\t ||  -\t ||  -\t ||  -\t|| .507184227\t|| .258983273\t|| .030120923\t|| .000909374\t|| .000005403 ||  -\n|-\n| align=\"left\" | 10\n| 30 || .030 || .032707283\t|| .0360044\t|| .040109181\t ||  -\t ||  -\t ||  -\t ||  -\t ||  -\t|| .659046577\t|| .189909911\t|| .01204378\t|| .000178479\t|| .000000388\n|-\n| align=\"left\" | 11\n| 20 || .020 || .022015249\t|| .024496655\t|| .027625001\t ||  -\t ||  -\t ||  -\t ||  -\t ||  -\t ||  -\t|| .775877187\t|| .125980501\t|| .003983749\t|| .000021657\n|-\n| align=\"left\" | 12\n| 15 ||  .015\t|| .016589133\t|| .018555684\t|| .021048948\t ||  -\t ||  -\t ||  -\t ||  -\t ||  -\t ||  -\t ||  -\t|| .861019923\t|| .06704081\t|| .000745502\n|-\n| align=\"left\" | 13\n| 10 || .010 || .011110696\t|| .012491705\t|| .014251824\t ||  -\t ||  -\t ||  -\t ||  -\t ||  -\t ||  -\t ||  -\t ||  -\t|| .928791559\t|| .023354216\n|-\n| align=\"left\" | 14\n| 5 || .005\t|| .005580727\t|| .006306033\t|| .007235003\t ||  -\t ||  -\t ||  -\t ||  -\t ||  -\t ||  -\t ||  -\t ||  -\t ||  -\t|| .975878236\n|}\n\nIn the event that teams finish with the same record, each tied team receives the ''average'' of the total number of combinations for the positions that they occupy.  In 2007, the [[Minnesota Timberwolves]] and the [[Portland Trail Blazers]] tied for the sixth worst record. The average of the 6th and 7th positions in the lottery was taken, resulting in each team getting 53 combinations (the average of 63 and 43).  Should the average number not be an [[integer]], a coin flip is then used to determine which team or teams receive the extra combination.  The result of the coin flip is also used to determine who receives the earlier pick in the event that neither of the tied teams wins one of the first four picks via the lottery.\n\nThe lottery is conducted with witnesses (from the accounting firm [[Ernst & Young]]) verifying that all fourteen balls are represented once as they are placed in the lottery machine. The balls are placed in the machine for 20 seconds to randomize before the first ball is drawn. The remaining three balls are drawn at 10-second intervals. NBA officials determine which team holds the winning combination and that franchise is awarded the #1 overall draft pick. The four balls are returned to the machine and the process is repeated to determine the second and third picks. In the event that a combination belongs to a team that has already won its pick (or if the one unassigned combination comes up), the round is repeated until a unique winner is determined. Prior to the 2019 draft, when the first three teams had been determined, the remaining picks were given out based on regular season record with the worst teams getting the highest picks. This assured each team that it could drop no more than three spots from its projected draft position.  Beginning with the 2019 draft, the number of combinations drawn is increased from 3 to 4, with the remaining picks still assigned based on regular season record.  A team then drops no more than four spots from its projected position.\n\nIn a case where a lottery team trades its pick to a playoff team, the playoff team assumes the lottery team's position in all draft lottery situations, unless provisioned by the conditions of the trade.\n\n==Lottery ceremony==\n{{See also|National Basketball Association criticisms and controversies}}\n\nThe drawing of the ping-pong balls is conducted in private, though observed by independent auditors and representatives from each team.  The results are subsequently presented in a televised unveiling (formerly broadcast as a short ceremony prior to or during halftime of an NBA playoff game, but since the mid-2010s, presented as an hour-long special by [[NBA on ESPN|ESPN]]), in which the order of the lottery is announced in reverse order, from the fourteenth selection to the first. Representatives from each NBA franchise with a lottery pick are present at the lottery ceremony.\n\nThe decision of not showing the ping-pong balls live has fueled speculation that the NBA occasionally fixes the draft lottery if it can benefit the league. The speculation originated with the 1985 draft lottery that sent Patrick Ewing to New York, with the theory being that the NBA wanted to send the best player in the draft to New York to increase ratings in a large television market. At that time, the NBA used seven envelopes in a tumbler representing the seven teams with the worst record. Some have speculated<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.usatoday.com/sports/basketball/nba/2009-05-18-3301876890_x.htm | work=USA Today | title=Griffin the big gift at lottery's 25th anniversary | date=May 18, 2009 | accessdate=May 20, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=http://articles.latimes.com/1985-05-14/sports/sp-19104_1_draft-lottery | work=Los Angeles Times | title=NBA's New Showtime: It's Called the Lottery | first=Sam | last=McManis | date=May 14, 1985 | accessdate=May 20, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nbadraft/story?id=1383452 |title=NBA out to prove conspiracy theorists wrong |first=Darren |last=Rovell |date=May 16, 2002 |publisher=ESPN |accessdate=April 8, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121104101847/http://sports.espn.go.com/nbadraft/story?id=1383452 |archivedate=November 4, 2012 }}</ref> that the envelope containing the Knicks logo was refrigerated beforehand, enabling [[David Stern]] to recognize and select it. Another conspiracy theory suggests that one of the seven envelopes was thrown into the tumbler, causing one of the corners to fold. After the envelopes were mixed, Stern took a deep breath before reaching into the tumbler and picking the envelope with the folded corner.<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=bX1kMlG8c7Y</ref> No one has ever explained why all the other teams would go along with the fix. Afterward, the Draft Lottery Format was changed to the current ping-pong ball lottery in a private room with team representatives. However, despite the lack of any evidence, conspiracy theories still persist regarding the annual outcome of the lottery.<ref>{{cite news |last=Dengate |first=Jeff |title=Let the Ping-Pong Balls Fall |date=May 16, 2007 |work=NBA.com |url=http://www.nba.com/features/inside_lottery_050524.html |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68Oj2mcnc?url=http://www.nba.com/features/inside_lottery_050524.html |url-status=dead |archivedate=June 13, 2012 |access-date=March 3, 2007 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Schoenfield |first=David |title=The first lottery draft still rates the best |date=June 29, 2009 |publisher=ESPN |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/espn/page2/story?page=draftreview/090624 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090627133325/http://sports.espn.go.com/espn/page2/story?page=draftreview%2F090624 |url-status=live |archivedate=June 27, 2009 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Helin |first=Kurt |title=David Stern expects your draft conspiracy theories now |work=nbcsports.com |url=http://probasketballtalk.nbcsports.com/2012/06/11/david-stern-expects-your-draft-conspiracy-theories-now/ |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68OjHFNC0?url=http://probasketballtalk.nbcsports.com/2012/06/11/david-stern-expects-your-draft-conspiracy-theories-now/ |url-status=live |archivedate=June 13, 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=David Stern, Jim Rome battle on radio |date=June 13, 2012 |publisher=ESPN |url=http://espn.go.com/nba/story/_/id/8048426/nba-commissioner-david-stern-radio-host-jim-rome-get-lottery |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68OjVdgFu?url=http://espn.go.com/nba/story/_/id/8048426/nba-commissioner-david-stern-radio-host-jim-rome-get-lottery |url-status=live |archivedate=June 13, 2012 }}</ref>\n\n==Lottery winners==\n[[File:NBA Draft Lottery winners.svg|thumb|441x441px|Visual representation of the following table.]]\nThe largest upset in the lottery occurred in [[1993 NBA draft|1993]] when the Magic won the lottery with just a 1.5% chance to win. The second largest upsets occurred in [[2008 NBA draft|2008]] and [[2014 NBA draft|2014]] when the [[Chicago Bulls]] and [[Cleveland Cavaliers]] both won their respective lotteries with just a 1.7% chance.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=20601079&sid=a8oVsNTz65cA|title=Bulls Win NBA's Draft Lottery, Eye Beasley, Rose With Top Pick|last=Matuszewski|first=Erik|date=May 21, 2008|accessdate=August 22, 2009|work=Bloomberg|publisher=Bloomberg L.P}}</ref> In [[1999 NBA draft|1999]], the [[Charlotte Hornets]] also overcame long odds in the draft lottery when they won the third pick despite having the best record among all non-playoff teams. The Hornets only had a 1.83% chance of winning a top-three pick.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/news/lottery02_probabilities.html|title=NBA.com:Year-By-Year Lottery Probabilities}}</ref> Since the lottery was introduced in 1985, only 18 of 30 NBA teams have won the lottery. The [[Los Angeles Clippers]] have won five lotteries, although two of them were conveyed to other teams in trades prior to the lottery. The [[Orlando Magic]], [[Cleveland Cavaliers]], and [[Brooklyn Nets]] are second with three lottery wins each. Since the weighted lottery system was introduced in 1990, only seven teams with the worst record went on to win the lottery while only four teams with the second-worst record have won the lottery.\n\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Year\n!Team\n!Previous season<br>record\n!Lottery<br>chances\n!Probability\n![[List of first overall NBA draft picks|Player selected]]\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|[[1985 NBA draft|1985]]\n|align=\"left\"|[[New York Knicks]]\n|24\u201358 (3rd-worst)\n|align=\"center\"|\u2014\n|{{Ntsh|14.29}}14.29%{{#tag:ref|From 1985 to 1988, each of the 7 non-playoff teams had an equal chance to win the lottery, i.e. 14.29%.|group=lower-alpha|name=note_a}}\n|{{sortname|Patrick|Ewing}}\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|[[1986 NBA draft|1986]]\n|align=\"left\"|[[Los Angeles Clippers]]<br><small>(conveyed to the [[Cleveland Cavaliers]] via [[Philadelphia 76ers]])</small>{{#tag:ref|The Philadelphia 76ers obtained [[Los Angeles Clippers]]' first-round pick in a previous trade on October 6, 1979 that sent [[Joe Bryant]] to the Clippers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/clippers/history/transactions.html|title=All-Time Transactions|accessdate=August 22, 2009|work=NBA.com/Clippers|publisher=Turner Sports Interactive, Inc|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100221020635/http://www.nba.com/clippers/history/transactions.html|archive-date=February 21, 2010|url-status=dead}}</ref> On June 16, 1986, after the lottery and a day before the draft, the 76ers traded the first pick to the [[Cleveland Cavaliers]] in exchange for [[Roy Hinson]].<ref>{{cite basketball-reference|name=Roy Hinson|id=h/hinsoro01|date=April 8, 2012}}</ref>|group=lower-alpha}}\n|32\u201350 (7th-worst)\n|align=\"center\"|\u2014\n|{{Ntsh|14.29}}14.29%<ref group=lower-alpha name=note_a/>\n|{{sortname|Brad|Daugherty|dab=basketball}}\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|[[1987 NBA draft|1987]]\n|align=\"left\"|[[San Antonio Spurs]]\n|28\u201354 (4th-worst)\n|align=\"center\"|\u2014\n|{{Ntsh|14.29}}14.29%<ref group=lower-alpha name=note_a/>\n|{{sortname|David|Robinson}}\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|[[1988 NBA draft|1988]]\n|align=\"left\"|[[Los Angeles Clippers]]\n|17\u201365 (Worst)\n|align=\"center\"|\u2014\n|{{Ntsh|14.29}}14.29%<ref group=lower-alpha name=note_a/>\n|{{sortname|Danny|Manning}}\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|[[1989 NBA draft|1989]]\n|align=\"left\"|[[Sacramento Kings]]\n|27\u201355 (6th-worst)\n|align=\"center\"|\u2014\n|{{Ntsh|11.11}}11.11%{{#tag:ref|In 1989, each of the 9 non-playoff teams had an equal chance to win the lottery, i.e. 11.11%.|group=lower-alpha}}\n|{{sortname|Pervis|Ellison}}\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|[[1990 NBA draft|1990]]\n|align=\"left\"|[[New Jersey Nets]]\n|17\u201365 (Worst)\n|11 (out of 66)\n|{{Ntsh|16.67}}16.67%\n|{{sortname|Derrick|Coleman}}\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|[[1991 NBA draft|1991]]\n|align=\"left\"|[[Charlotte Hornets]]\n|26\u201356 (5th-worst)\n|7 (out of 66)\n|{{Ntsh|10.61}}10.61%\n|{{sortname|Larry|Johnson|dab=basketball, born 1969}}\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|[[1992 NBA draft|1992]]\n|align=\"left\"|[[Orlando Magic]]\n|21\u201361 (2nd-worst)\n|10 (out of 66)\n|{{Ntsh|15.15}}15.15%\n|{{sortname|Shaquille|O'Neal}}\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|[[1993 NBA draft|1993]]\n|align=\"left\"|[[Orlando Magic]]<br><small>(conveyed to [[Golden State Warriors|Golden State]] on draft night)</small>\n|41\u201341 (11th-worst)\n|1 (out of 66)\n|{{Ntsh|1.52}}1.52%\n|{{sortname|Chris|Webber}}\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|[[1994 NBA draft|1994]]\n|align=\"left\"|[[Milwaukee Bucks]]\n|20\u201362 (2nd-worst)\n|163 (out of 1000)\n|{{Ntsh|16.30}}16.30%\n|{{sortname|Glenn|Robinson}}\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|[[1995 NBA draft|1995]]\n|align=\"left\"|[[Golden State Warriors]]\n|26\u201356 (5th-worst)\n|94 (out of 1000)\n|{{Ntsh|9.40}}9.40%\n|{{sortname|Joe|Smith|dab=basketball}}\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|[[1996 NBA draft|1996]]\n|align=\"left\"|[[Philadelphia 76ers]]\n|18\u201364 (2nd-worst)\n|200 (out of 593){{#tag:ref|The [[Toronto Raptors]] and the [[Memphis Grizzlies|Vancouver Grizzlies]] were not eligible to win the lottery in 1996, 1997 and 1998 due to their expansion agreement. Therefore, their lottery combinations for the first pick were excluded.|group=lower-alpha|name=note_d}}\n|{{Ntsh|33.73}}33.73%\n|{{sortname|Allen|Iverson}}\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|[[1997 NBA draft|1997]]\n|align=\"left\"|[[San Antonio Spurs]]\n|20\u201362 (3rd-worst)\n|157 (out of 727)<ref group=lower-alpha name=note_d/>\n|{{Ntsh|21.60}}21.60%\n|{{sortname|Tim|Duncan}}\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|[[1998 NBA draft|1998]]\n|align=\"left\"|[[Los Angeles Clippers]]\n|17\u201365 (3rd-worst)\n|157 (out of 696)<ref group=lower-alpha name=note_d/>\n|{{Ntsh|22.56}}22.56%\n|{{sortname|Michael|Olowokandi}}\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|[[1999 NBA draft|1999]]\n|align=\"left\"|[[Chicago Bulls]]\n|13\u201337{{#tag:ref|Due to the [[1998\u201399 NBA lockout]], the [[1998\u201399 NBA season|season]] was shortened to 50 games per team.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/02/15/sports/basketball/15nba.html|title=N.B.A. and Union Are Discussing New Labor Deal|first=Howard|last=Beck|date=February 14, 2009|work=The New York Times |accessdate=February 22, 2009}}</ref>|group=lower-alpha}} (3rd-worst)\n|157 (out of 1000)\n|{{Ntsh|15.70}}15.70%\n|{{sortname|Elton|Brand}}\n